// url-shortener.arch — golden fixture (DGC-31)
//
// The textbook "design a URL shortener" system-design sketch: a client
// behind a load balancer that fans out to two API server instances, which
// share a Redis cache and a Postgres database. Click analytics are pushed
// onto a queue so the write path never blocks the redirect response.
//
// Read path  (GET /:code):
//   Client -> LB -> API Server -> Cache Redis (hit)  -> 302 redirect
//                              -> Postgres (miss, then warm the cache)
// Write path (POST /shorten):
//   Client -> LB -> API Server -> Postgres (insert code) -> Cache Redis (warm)
//
// Every API request also fires an analytics event onto a queue, decoupling
// the click-tracking write from the hot redirect path.

direction right

Client [icon: monitor]

Service tier {
  LB [icon: network, color: blue]
  API Server A [icon: server, color: orange]
  API Server B [icon: server, color: orange]
}

Data tier {
  Cache Redis [icon: redis, color: red]
  Postgres [icon: postgresql, color: blue]
  Analytics Queue [icon: list, color: pink]
}

Client > LB: HTTPS request
LB > API Server A, API Server B: round robin

API Server A > Cache Redis: GET short_code
API Server A > Postgres: fallback on cache miss
API Server A > Analytics Queue: click event

API Server B > Cache Redis: GET short_code
API Server B > Postgres: fallback on cache miss
API Server B > Analytics Queue: click event
